sum!` (and friends) completely ignore the initial values (and even allow separately supplying a scalar `init`).

It's worth noting that it's _far easier_ to write this implementation **and** get good performance if you can just use the output array as the initial value.  The semantics are simpler, too — it completely avoids the empty array issue of deciding whether to divine up a return value or to error with "reducing over an empty collection is not allowed". ","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JuliaLang/julia/issues/comments/2265844966/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

